About
The host of Travel Channel's #1 rated series Ghost Adventures is giving everyone a chance to experience the spine-chilling vibe of the spirit world. Reality star and author Zak Bagans has turned a historic downtown Las Vegas mansion into a mecca of the macabre - a haunted museum. The 11,000-square foot property built in 1938 is located near South Las Vegas Boulevard and was originally owned by Cyril S. Wengert, a prominent businessman. Through the years, hostile spirits have been rumored to roam the halls terrorizing past occupants, family members who passed away there whose energy remains. Long-time Las Vegans even claim dark rituals took place in the home's basement during the 1970's. Paranormal enthusiasts visiting Zak Bagans' The Haunted Museum will venture down creepy winding hallways and secret passages into more than 30 rooms that rival scenes from Hollywood horror films, setting the stage for frightening facts about each paranormal pieces.
Duration: 2-3 hours

    Zak Bagans The Haunted Museum - If you don't pay extra - they let you and everyone else know!
    The tour itself was very informative and the information and exhibits made it worth the price of the general admission. We did not do the RIP as the cost was about $40 more per person and that was beyond our budget. Our first tour guide was great! During the experience you will be handed off to several tour guides, some great, some downright rude. The biggest issue we had is their constant need to point out to us and everyone in our group (13 people) that we did NOT purchase the RIP advanced experience. Instead of having a group for general admission and one for the advanced experience, we were constantly singled out, told to wait behind, don't look at an exhibit. this is not for you. We were embarrassed as this was done at least 5-6 times during the 3 hour tour. A three hour tour which is all walking, there is no place to sit, and you are told not to lean on anything. No bathroom breaks and at one point you are given the option to drink from a water cooler, but could not take drinks along the tour. In some rooms it was very hot, stuffy and we had to pile into some rooms where you had to shift just so a door could close. Towards the end of the tour, they got backed up and our guide had to leave us to assist others. As with most tours when completed you are asked to pass an area where you can give a tip, of the 13 people in our group, only one person left a tip! We started our our at 6pm and it ended after a bit over 3 hours, when we went to leave we were told we had to exit around the building as the parking lot was now locked. Overall we were very disappointed for a trip that we had planned months for, we came to Las Vegas from Texas specifically for this tour, and left feeling embarrassed, annoyed tired, hot and with headaches from the scents they force into the rooms. The property is in a less than desirable area (no fault of theirs as it is where the haunted house is located but beware, lots of homeless people around), when we first arrived there we were excited to find parking in front, only to be told no, we cant park there, its for a private party (no signs up, we were told after we parked that we had to go around the block and park in back) there is not enough parking in their spots so they directed us to the parking next door and said that hopefully it will not get towed as they do not own the whole lot.

Chris B
Coventry, UK225 contributions
Fun, spooky day out
Oct 2024 Solo
First off I want to set out that I write this review from the viewpoint of someone who doesn't actually believe in the supernatural, but just enjoys seeing cool, spooky stuff, so no offence intended to anyone that does - also I had no idea who Zak Bagans was before visiting here, had no idea he had multiple TV shows & just thought it was a funky name to put in the title. Having said that, I had a really fun time visiting the museum. No I didnt feel any supernatural presence at any point or see anything unexplainable, but I did see a whole host of really interesting items that have legitimate crazy backstories to them, in a really well stocked museum of oddities and curios. The fact that the tour goes on for a full 3 hours without having any standing around and waiting or filler parts is outstanding value for money, the tour guide was full of information and enthusiasm throughout and just the size of the museum (it really didnt LOOK that big from the outside) is just incredible. Its really cool to see so many different artefacts that have been gathered from all sorts of spooky incidents over the years, whether you believe or not, just seeing objects that were in some way connected to terrible occurances or unexplainable mysteries is still pretty cool. I will say I was torn a few times between "this is cool" and "not sure about this" with some objects, especially when it came to personal effects of deceased victims/murderers, as interesting as it was to see, sometimes I did think some objects were a bit too much (Patrick Swayzes tooth that his family didnt want sold being a major one), but overall I think the interesting factor outwayed the occasional ick factor. If you're after a spooky afternoon sifting through some macabre objects, then I'd definitely recommend giving the tour a go. I did pay for the RIP/VIP package which gives you access to a few extra rooms that you dont get without it, honestly, not sure it was worth it as the extra rooms werent as good as I was expecting, but you do get a t-shirt as part of the package which is worth more than the upgrade anyway so its probably worth it just for that.
Written October 28, 2024
